<section class="card">

  <h2>What Is a “Killing Frost”?</h2>

  <p>
    Gardeners often hear the phrase “killing frost,” but it does not simply mean 32°F.
  </p>

  <p>
    A killing frost generally refers to a cold event severe enough to end the growing season
    for tender crops. For many warm-season vegetables,
    that threshold is commonly around 28°F for several hours —
    though the exact temperature depends on the crop and conditions.
  </p>

  <p>
    In other words, while 32°F may cause surface frost and leaf damage,
    temperatures closer to 28°F are much more likely to cause irreversible tissue injury.
  </p>

  <p>
    If you’d like a deeper explanation of how killing frosts are defined,
    how they relate to frost dates,
    and why they matter for seasonal planning,
    read our full guide:
